Consider an infinitely long cylindrical thread of initial radius $R_0$
composed of an Oldroyd-B fluid. The fluid has total viscosity
$\eta = \eta_s + \eta_p$ (where $\eta_s$ is the solvent viscosity and
$\eta_p$ is the polymer viscosity), a single relaxation time $\lambda$,
density $\rho$, and surface tension $\sigma$. The thread is perturbed
axisymmetrically with wavenumber $k$, so the free surface is at
$r = R(z, t) = R_0 + \epsilon(t) e^{ikz}$.

**(a)** Write the full governing equations. Specify: (i) mass conservation
for an incompressible fluid, (ii) momentum balance including the
viscoelastic stress tensor $\boldsymbol{\tau}_p$ satisfying the
upper-convected Maxwell (UCM) constitutive equation,
(iii) the kinematic boundary condition at the free surface
$r = R(z,t)$, and (iv) the dynamic (stress) boundary condition relating
the jump in normal stress to the Laplace pressure.

**(b)** Linearize all equations about the cylindrical base state (radius
$R_0$, zero velocity, isotropic polymer stress
$\boldsymbol{\tau}_p^{(0)} = G\mathbf{I}$ where $G = \eta_p/\lambda$ is
the elastic modulus). Derive the dispersion relation $\omega(k)$ for the
perturbation growth rate. Show that it depends on the Deborah number
$\mathrm{De} = \lambda/\tau_c$ and the viscosity ratio
$\beta = \eta_s/(\eta_s + \eta_p)$, where $\tau_c = \eta R_0/\sigma$ is
the characteristic capillary timescale.

**(c)** Analyze the dispersion relation in limiting cases. Show that for
$\mathrm{De} = 0$ (Newtonian limit), the classic Rayleigh result is
recovered:
$$\omega^2 = \frac{\sigma k}{\rho R_0^2}(1 - k^2R_0^2)
\frac{I_1(kR_0)}{I_0(kR_0)}.$$

For $\mathrm{De} > 0$, show that the growth rate is everywhere reduced
relative to the Newtonian case. Find the critical condition on
$\mathrm{De}$ and $\beta$ above which the thread is completely
stabilized against the Rayleigh-Plateau instability ($\omega^2 \leq 0$
for all $k$).

**(d)** In the nonlinear regime, the thread thins and develops the
"beads-on-a-string" morphology — nearly spherical drops connected by thin
elastic filaments. Using a one-dimensional slender-jet approximation
($R(z,t) \ll R_0$, axial variations slow), derive the evolution equation
for the minimum thread radius $R_{\min}(t)$. Show that:
$$R_{\min}(t) \sim
\begin{cases}
R_0 - \dfrac{\sigma}{3\eta R_0}(t_c - t), & \text{Newtonian }(\mathrm{De} \ll 1), \\[6pt]
R_0\exp\!\left(-\dfrac{t}{3\lambda}\right), & \text{elastic-dominated }(\mathrm{De} \gg 1).
\end{cases}$$

Identify the physical regime where each scaling applies.

**(e)** An experimentalist measures the filament lifetime $t_f$ (the time
from initial perturbation to breakup) for a series of Oldroyd-B fluids
with varying $\lambda$. They find $t_f \propto \lambda^{2/3}$, not the
linear scaling $t_f \propto \lambda$ predicted by the Oldroyd-B model.
Explain this discrepancy by considering the finite extensibility of
polymer chains. Introducing the FENE-P (Finitely Extensible Nonlinear
Elastic – Peterlin) model, which modifies the stress evolution when the
polymer extension approaches its maximum $L_{\max}$, derive the modified
scaling $t_f \propto \lambda^{2/3}$ and identify the physical origin of
the exponent.

```figure caption="Capillary thinning of a viscoelastic thread. A cylindrical thread develops axisymmetric varicose perturbations, forming beads connected by thinning elastic filaments."
